This adds a `svelte/motion` file, with two exports — `tweened` and (TODO) `spring`. These functions return a `writable` store, except that `store.set` and `store.update` change to their target value gradually, and return a Promise.

## `tweened`

The API for `tweened` looks like this:

```js
import { tweened } from 'svelte/motion';
import { elasticOut } from 'svelte/easing';

const coords = tweened({ x: 0, y: 0 }, {
  // these are default options that will be used
  // if none are provided for a given tween
  duration: 800,
  easing: elasticOut
});

window.addEventListener('click', e => {
  coords.set({ x: e.clientX, y: e.clientY }, {
    // these will optionally override
    // individual default options
  });
});
```

There's also `coords.update`:

```js
coords.update((target_value, actual_value) => {
  x: target_value.x + 100,
  y: target_value.y
}, opts);
```

Complete set of options:

* `delay` — how long in milliseconds before the value should start changing. Any previous tweens won't be cancelled until the new one starts. Defaults to `0`
* `duration` — how long it should take, in milliseconds. Defaults to `400`. Alternatively, pass a function that receives `current_value` and `target_value` arguments (useful if you want larger tweens to take longer, for example)
* `easing` — an easing function, e.g. from `svelte/easing`
* `interpolate` — a custom `(current_value, target_value) => t => value` function. Svelte tweens numbers, dates, and arrays or objects containing numbers or dates (however deeply nested) as long as everything is the same 'shape' — so it will tween `{ x: 0, y: 0 }` to `{ x: 100, y: 100 }` for example. But it won't tween things like colour strings, matrix strings etc without a custom interpolator.


## `spring`

```js
import { spring } from 'svelte/motion';

const coords = spring({ x: 0, y: 0 }, {
  // these are default options that will be used
  // if none are provided for a given tween
  stiffness: 0.1,
  damping: 0.5
});

window.addEventListener('click', e => {
  coords.set({ x: e.clientX, y: e.clientY });
});
```

`spring` gives you less direct control, but can result in more pleasing motion depending on what you're trying to do. There are two options, `stiffness` and `damping`, that control the spring's physics — both are values between 0 and 1. You can change these values after the fact with e.g. `spring.stiffness = 0.5`.

Custom interpolators aren't supported, because they don't really make much sense here. You can interpolate the values that `tweened` supports out of the box.

## Coordination

There's some central coordination that runs all current tasks on `requestAnimationFrame` (but only when `tasks.size > 0`) and handles promise resolution etc. It may make sense to use this for element transitions and animations as well. We might even want to expose it to userland — the API is fairly simple:

```js
const { abort, promise } = add_task(() => {
  // this will run on the next animation frame, and
  // on every frame after that until it returns a
  // falsy value, at which point the promise fulfils
});

promise.then(() => {
  // the task is complete
});

// stop calling the function. the promise will
// never resolve, if it didn't already:
abort();
```

Things to consider:

* For testability, we might want to expose hooks that make it easy to advance to the next frame (or an arbitrary future frame). At the moment this is done for transitions in the test suite somewhat hackily (search for `raf.tick`)
* Similarly, it would be neat if we could control time globally across a Svelte app, the way Edward Faulkner does in [this talk](https://youtu.be/4JofVQ3nGrw?t=1267). Really helpful for debugging animations
* `requestAnimationFrame` is fine most of the time, but on many VR displays (e.g. you're using Svelte with [A-Frame](https://aframe.io/) you need a faster refresh rate than 60Hz, and should use [vrDisplayInstance.requestAnimationFrame](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/VRDisplay/requestAnimationFrame) instead. It'd nice if there was an easy way to do this (or if it was even taken care of for us?)

This adds some missing types to the Store's declaration file.

`set`'s `void` return type is optional but there are compiler options that make it required, so it doesn't hurt to provide it for users.

`compute`'s third argument was missing and I had a couple of options: either go with the simpler `(...deps: any[]) => any` or fiddle a bit with TypeScript.... I don't think it went _completely_ overboard:

```typescript
interface Tuple<T extends any, L extends number> extends Array<T> {
	0: T;
	length: L;
}

declare function compute<L extends number>(
	key: string,
	dependencies: Tuple<string, L>,
	fn: (...dependencies: Tuple<any, L>) => any,
): void;
```

This has the benefit of reporting errors when the function's prototype doesn't match the specified dependencies. [See error reporting in use](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#src=interface%20Tuple%3CT%20extends%20any%2C%20L%20extends%20number%3E%20extends%20Array%3CT%3E%20%7B%0D%0A%20%20%20%200%3A%20T%3B%0D%0A%09length%3A%20L%3B%0D%0A%7D%0D%0A%0D%0Adeclare%20function%20compute%3CL%20extends%20number%3E(%0D%0A%09key%3A%20string%2C%0D%0A%09dependencies%3A%20Tuple%3Cstring%2C%20L%3E%2C%0D%0A%09fn%3A%20(...dependencies%3A%20Tuple%3Cany%2C%20L%3E)%20%3D%3E%20any%2C%0D%0A)%3A%20void%3B%0D%0A%0D%0Acompute('area'%2C%20%5B'width'%2C%20'height'%5D%2C%20(w%2C%20h)%20%3D%3E%20w%20*%20h)%3B%0D%0Acompute('volume'%2C%20%5B'width'%2C%20'height'%2C%20'length'%5D%2C%20(w%2C%20h%2C%20l)%20%3D%3E%20w%20*%20h%20*%20l)%3B%0D%0A%0D%0Acompute('area'%2C%20%5B'width'%2C%20'height'%5D%2C%20(w)%20%3D%3E%20w)%3B%0D%0Acompute('volume'%2C%20%5B'width'%2C%20'height'%2C%20'length'%5D%2C%20(w%2C%20h%2C%20l%2C%20x)%20%3D%3E%20w%20*%20h%20*%20l%20*%20x)%3B%0D%0A).

